      "anchor_proposed": {
        "vr_id": 6971,
        "reference": "Isa 52:13",
        "strongs": "H7919A",
        "translit": "sa.khal",
        "anchor_rationale": "'Behold, my Servant shall act wisely; he shall be high and lifted up, and shall be exalted.' The verb (sa.khal) and its consequence (exaltation) are stated in their most concentrated form. The Servant's wise action is both inner quality and productive outcome — the inner discernment produces the exaltation. No verse makes the phenomenon clearer."
      }
    },
    {
      "code": "M15-D-VCG02",
      "label": "Inner discriminating act: discernment, doubt, distinction (diakrinō)",
      "context_description": "The term names the inner act of discriminating — of making evaluative distinctions between persons or things, or of the self-dividing inner state of doubt. The range includes: reading signs (natural vs spiritual), the doubting heart split between faith and hesitation, the Spirit's command to make no distinction between Jew and Gentile, self-judgment in the Lord's Supper, and weighing prophecy. Inner-being phenomenon: inner discriminating act or self-division.",
