      "anchor_proposed": {
        "vr_id": 50887,
        "reference": "1Cor 11:31",
        "strongs": "G1252",
        "translit": "diakrinō",
        "anchor_rationale": "'But if we judged ourselves truly, we would not be judged.' The self-referential discriminating act — diakrinō applied to oneself — is named in its most direct form: true self-discernment would preempt divine judgment. The verse makes clear that the inner act of discriminating evaluation has moral consequences whether directed outward (toward others) or inward (toward self)."
      }
